-- #609 regression, ARG-POSITION leg (argImplDictRoutesForEncl).  The same defect as
-- multiparam_impl_selection.mdk one leg over: `routeKey` selected the method's impl
-- on the full param vector, but the SELECTED IMPL'S OWN `requires`-context routes
-- were still chosen on the arg-0 mono alone.  `[mono]` length-mismatches a
-- multi-param impl's `itys`, so entryHeadMatches fell back to arg-0, both siblings
-- matched, entryCovers found them incomparable (they are genuinely disjoint, so
-- declaration-time coherence never rejected them), and pickMostSpecificEntry took
-- the FIRST-DECLARED.  DICT-SEMANTICS §6 C2: the impl dispatched to and the impl
-- whose context is discharged must be the SAME impl; §6 C3: not a function of
-- declaration order.
--
-- Goal `Ix (Box Int) Char` dispatches to the Char impl (1 require) but was routed
-- the Bool impl's TWO requires-dicts, shifting every later argument — so `(Box x)`
-- destructured a dict cell:
--     runtime error [E-NONEXHAUSTIVE-MATCH]: non-exhaustive match
-- on eval AND native.  Correct output is 2050 (bar 1 + 2000).
--
-- ⚠️ Why the requires must differ in COUNT, not just in interface: the dict cell is
-- a TYPE tag (the emitted `@mdk_dc_0 = [1 x i64] [193460240]` is the `Int` tag, and
-- is shared with println's dict), and the routes are built from the head subst — so
-- two siblings whose requires range over the SAME tyvar `a` produce the SAME dict
-- whichever one is picked, and the interface is re-chosen at the use site by a
-- method-specific dispatcher (`@mdk_disp_bar_0_1`).  Probes with equal-arity
-- requires printed the CORRECT answer and were false negatives.  Foo/Baz/Bar each
-- need TWO impls for the same reason: a sole impl devirtualizes to a direct call and
-- never consults the dict at all.
data Box a = Box a

interface Foo a where
  foo : a -> Int
impl Foo Int where
  foo x = 7
impl Foo Bool where
  foo x = 8

interface Baz a where
  baz : a -> Int
impl Baz Int where
  baz x = 300
impl Baz Bool where
  baz x = 400

interface Bar a where
  bar : a -> Int
impl Bar Int where
  bar x = 50
impl Bar Bool where
  bar x = 60

interface Ix c i where
  ix : c -> i -> Int

impl Ix (Box a) Bool requires Foo a, Baz a where
  ix (Box x) i = foo x + baz x

impl Ix (Box a) Char requires Bar a where
  ix (Box x) i = bar x + 2000

main = println (ix (Box 1) 'z')
